    {
      "id": "/page/0/TextInlineMath/18",
      "block_type": "TextInlineMath",
      "html": "<p block-type=\"TextInlineMath\">If the distribution of accumulated capital (wealth) at the horizon is the criterion for deciding on an investment strategy, then the rate of growth of capital becomes the determining factor when the horizon is distant. For fixed d and i.i.d <math display=\"inline\">V_i</math>, the growth rate converges to the mean growth rate as <math display=\"inline\">n</math> increases, so considering the average growth rate between <math display=\"inline\">t_1</math> and <math display=\"inline\">t_2</math>, for strategy <math display=\"inline\">\\mathbf{X} = (X(t_1), \\ldots, X(t_1 + (n-1)d)),</math></p>",
